{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01Td9MFAfpAfkBtpzcgJkqKp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All requirements are met. Summary of what was wrong and the fix:\n\n## Diagnosis\n- RabbitMQ was already correctly exposing metrics — the `rabbitmq_prometheus` plugin was enabled and port **15692** (`/metrics`) was reachable on all 3 pods.\n- The only problem was Prometheus's config: it had **no scrape job for RabbitMQ** — it only scraped itself.\n\n## Fix (native resources only — just a ConfigMap + Deployment restart)\n1. **Added a `rabbitmq` scrape job** to the `prometheus-config` ConfigMap targeting the three pod FQDNs via the existing headless service:\n   - `rabbitmq-{0,1,2}.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local:15692`\n2. **Added a recording rule** (`rabbitmq_up` = `up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}`). The native RabbitMQ plugin (3.12) does **not** emit a `rabbitmq_up` metric, so I aliased Prometheus's synthetic per-target `up` metric to satisfy the `rabbitmq_up` requirement.\n3. Restarted the `prometheus` Deployment to load the new config/rules.\n\n## Verification\n- ✅ Metrics exposed on port 15692 `/metrics` on all pods.\n- ✅ Prometheus shows **3 RabbitMQ targets UP / 3**.\n- ✅ `rabbitmq_up` query returns **3 samples** (one per pod, value `1`).\n- ✅ RabbitMQ unchanged and healthy — all 3 pods `Running 1/1` (no restarts). Only the Prometheus ConfigMap was modified."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":604,"cache_read_input_tokens":38598,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":604},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"668138ba-a546-4aff-8add-982deb772bbe","uuid":"d8dd71b7-a735-4d7c-a92d-32f485e7a1cc","request_id":"req_011CcAdFxbF9utrJt2hXBuvz"}
